glm_assumptions.html

Every model in the GLM family carries the general assumptions we’ve discussed on other pages in this series (e.g., correct distributional family, linearity on the link scale, no influential outliers). But some model families also carry assumptions that are specific to their particular structure: assumptions that don’t arise in binary logistic regression or Poisson models, but that become important the moment you extend to ordinal or nominal outcomes. This page covers two such assumptions: The proportional odds assumption is specific to ordered logit and ordered probit models. It also happens to be one of the more commonly violated (and ignored) assumptions in the political science literature (Long and Freese 2014). The independence of irrelevant alternatives (IIA) assumption is specific to the multinomial logit model, and it’s one of the most commonly misunderstood (Patty and Penn 2019). Both are worth understanding because they have clear implications for how to specify your model and how to interpret its results. It’s also good to be aware that there is a lot of debate in the literature about whether/when/how these assumptions matter, since you may come across reviewers who have contrary opinions on the subject.

glm_mixed_diag.html

Mixed models — also called multilevel or hierarchical models — are the appropriate tool whenever your data have a clustered structure: survey respondents nested within countries, students within schools, repeated observations on the same individual, roll-call votes within legislators. The clustering structure means that observations within the same group tend to be more similar to each other than to observations in other groups, and ignoring this dependence understates standard errors and overstates precision. Diagnosing a mixed model requires attention to two levels simultaneously. At the observation level (level 1), you’re asking whether the fixed effects are correctly specified and whether individual observations fit the model well. At the group level (level 2), you’re asking whether the random effects structure is appropriate and whether any groups behave in ways the model doesn’t anticipate. This page works through the full diagnostic workflow for mixed GLMs, starting with the question of whether a mixed model is warranted at all (via the ICC), moving through model-building decisions, and then covering the observation-level and group-level diagnostics that should accompany every fitted mixed model. The tools throughout are modern: DHARMa for simulation-based residuals, performance for a suite of model checks, and effect plots for communicating what the random effects are actually telling you. The residuals page on this site covers the theoretical basis for quantile residuals and the DHARMa workflow in detail. This page applies those tools specifically to the mixed model context and adds the diagnostics that are unique to models with random effects.

glm_model_fit.html

In ordinary least squares regression, you get an R^2 at the bottom of every output table, and interpreting it is second nature: it’s the proportion of variance in explained by the model, and it ranges from 0 to 1. You know what a “good” looks like for your field. You know how to compare two models using it. Generalized linear models take all of that away. Because GLMs don’t minimize a sum of squared residuals, there’s no natural R^2. Because they use maximum likelihood estimation, the notion of “explained variance” doesn’t cleanly apply. And because different model families have different distributional scales, you can’t even compare a goodness-of-fit metric across a logistic regression and a Poisson model the way you’d compare across two OLS models. But all hope is not lost! What GLMs do have is deviance. Once you understand what deviance is and where it comes from, most of the goodness-of-fit apparatus for GLMs falls into place. Let’s explore this idea, then we can talk about the pseudo-R^2 statistics that borrow deviance’s logic, the information criteria and likelihood ratio tests used for model comparison, posterior predictive checks, and finally how all of this changes (a little) for mixed models.

glm_outliers_nonlinearity.html

Outliers and nonlinearity are two of the most common sources of model misfit in applied work, and in GLMs they have an interesting relationship: each can make the other harder to detect. An outlier at an extreme predictor value can pull a coefficient estimate in a direction that makes the fit look curved when it isn’t. Conversely, genuine nonlinearity in a predictor can produce a cluster of residuals with the same pattern as a group of outliers. Working through these two problems together, and understanding how they interact, is more useful than treating them as separate checklist items. This page covers outlier detection and influence analysis first, then turns to nonlinearity. It emphasizes quantile residuals and DHARMa simulation-based diagnostics throughout — the same tools introduced in the residuals page. If you haven’t read that page yet, the key point to carry into this one is: for non-Gaussian GLMs, standard Pearson and deviance residuals are not reliable for detecting either outliers or nonlinear patterns, because their distributions are not normal even under a well-specified model. Quantile residuals solve this.

glm_residuals.html

If you’ve spent any time with linear regression, you know that residuals are the workhorses of diagnostics. You plot them, you stare at them, you look for patterns that shouldn’t be there. The process feels almost meditative by the time you’ve done it enough times. So here’s a question worth asking before we go any further: what exactly is a residual? In a linear model, the answer seems almost too simple to state. A residual is the difference between what you observed and what the model predicted:𝑟𝑖=𝑦𝑖−𝑦̂ 𝑖That’s it. And because OLS models have normally distributed errors by assumption, and because the residuals are consistent estimators of those errors, the residuals themselves should look approximately normal. Their distribution is familiar. You know what “good” looks like .Generalized linear models break all of this. The response variable is no longer assumed to be normally distributed — it might be binary, or a count, or ordinal. The conditional mean is no longer a simple linear function of the predictors; it’s a transformation of one. And the variance of the outcome is no longer constant — it depends on the mean in a way that’s specific to the distributional family. All of the comfortable intuitions you’ve built up about residuals need to be revised.This page works through what residuals mean in the GLM context, why the most natural choices turn out to have serious limitations, and what current best practice looks like. We’ll end up at randomized quantile residuals (Dunn and Smyth 1996) and their simulation-based cousins from the DHARMa package (Hartig 2022) — and you’ll understand why these approaches work, not just how to run them.

ols_diagnostics.html

Every time you estimate an OLS regression model, you’re making a set of assumptions. The assumptions aren’t just bureaucratic fine print — when they’re violated, your coefficient estimates can be biased, your standard errors can be wrong, and your inferences can lead you astray. The goal of diagnostics is to find out which assumptions are violated, how badly, and what to do about it. The problem is that the diagnostic steps can feel like a jumbled bag of tests and plots with no obvious logic connecting them. This document is my attempt to give you a clear, principled workflow — a sequence you can follow every single time you estimate an OLS model, with a rationale for why each step comes where it does. Here’s the key logic: Some diagnostic problems contaminate others. Run diagnostics in the order that lets each step work on the cleanest possible version of your model. This is why order matters. Unmodeled nonlinearity creates artificial outliers. Artificial outliers distort heteroscedasticity tests. Multicollinearity inflates standard errors in ways that look like estimation problems. Fix things in sequence, and the later diagnostics become more interpretable. Jump around, and you’ll be chasing ghosts.

ols_multicollinearity.html

In this document, we’re going to talk about multicollinearity and its effects on our regression models. Multicollinearity is a situation in which two or more predictor variables in a regression model are highly correlated with each other. This can cause problems for our regression models because it can make it difficult to determine the individual effect of each predictor variable on the dependent variable. To deal with this issue, we need to identify it and then take steps to address it. First, I’ll walk you through what multicollinearity is. Then, I’ll show you an example of how to diagnose the problem and some ways to address it. Among the possible solutions is to use principal components factor analysis (often abbreviated as PCF) to (1) reduce the dimensionality of a battery of questions to help deal with problematic multicollinearity, and (2) incorporate multiple measures of a single underlying concept without risking high multicollinearity (or to use as a more precise measure of a dependent variable). We’ll learn how to implement that in R.

ols_outliers.html

In this document, we’re going to explore outliers and influential observations in regression analysis. An outlier is an observation that falls far away from the rest of the data points. While all influential observations are outliers, not all outliers are influential. Understanding the difference between these types of observations and knowing how to diagnose and handle them is crucial for building robust regression models.First, I’ll walk you through what outliers are and why they matter. Then, we’ll explore the different types of outliers using simulated data to see how they affect our regression models. Finally, I’ll show you practical diagnostic tools for identifying problematic outliers in real data and discuss strategies for dealing with them.